“The temperament of Parini differed widely from that of Leo XIII ; his was acrid, violent, unsparing; the Pope's is exactly the reverse. But both are shown to have many points of resemblance when we remember that, leaving the poets of North Europe out of count for the sake of argument, Parini was probably the greatest satir-ist since the days of Juvenal, though possessed of qualities which made him resemble both Virgil and Horace, as the Cardinal Vice- Ohancellor has shown in an eloquent discourse.
